04382nam a22005415i 9780226554259DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20092009ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226554259  a(DE-B1597)524313  a(OCoLC)1086543042  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aPS153.N5bM89 2009eb 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a810.9/35782221 aMuyumba, Walton M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Shadow and the Act :bBlack Intellectual Practice, Jazz Improvisation, and Philosophical Pragmatism /cWalton M. Muyumba. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (208 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. Vamping ’til Ready -- tMovement I. Three Ways of Looking at a Yardbird: Charlie Parker and the Theorization of Jazz Improvisation in the Work of Ralph Ellison, James Baldwin, and LeRoi Jones/Amiri Baraka -- tMovement II. Black Is, Black Ain’t: Violence, Black Masculinity, and the Novel as Democratic Symbol -- tMovement III. Cutting Session: Baldwin as Prizefighting Intellectual, Baldwin as Improvising Intellectual -- tMovement IV. Improvising over the Changes: Improvisation as Intellectual and Aesthetic Practice in the Transitional Poems of LeRoi Jones/Amiri Baraka -- tCoda -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tReference List -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThough often thought of as rivals, Ralph Ellison, James Baldwin, and Amiri Baraka shared a range of interests, especially a passion for music. Jazz, in particular, was a decisive influence on their thinking, and, as The Shadow and the Act reveals, they drew on their insights into the creative process of improvisation to analyze race and politics in the civil rights era. In this inspired study, Walton M. Muyumba situates them as a jazz trio, demonstrating how Ellison, Baraka, and Baldwin’s individual works form a series of calls and responses with each other. Muyumba connects their writings on jazz to the philosophical tradition of pragmatism, particularly its support for more freedom for individuals and more democratic societies. He examines the way they responded to and elaborated on that lineage, showing how they significantly broadened it by addressing the African American experience, especially its aesthetics. Ultimately, Muyumba contends, the trio enacted pragmatist principles by effectively communicating the social and political benefits of African Americans fully entering society, thereby compelling America to move closer to its democratic ideals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aImprovisation (Music). 0aJazz in literature. 0aJazzxHistory and criticism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aamiri baraka, james baldwin, ralph ellison, music, jazz, race, racism, black, improvisation, civil rights, politics, history, pragmatism, democracy, freedom, individual, aesthetics, african american, inclusion, diversity, literature, violence, masculinity, gender, le roi jones, poetry, novels, nonfiction, belonging, blackness, men.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022655423540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226554259423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226554259/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles